Unfortunately the solution is flawed. There is a sort of bug with `ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor`, also reported in [this question][1]: cancelling a submitted task does not fully release the memory resources associated with the task; the resources are released only when the task expires.

If you therefore create a `TimeoutThreadPoolExecutor` with a fairly long expiration time (a typical usage), and submit tasks fast enough, you end up filling the memory - even though the tasks actually completed successfully.

